{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652534"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:41:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:41:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18543"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18543"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.18,0,0.09,0.68]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11275"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75615"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11275"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18543"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61133"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10896"},{"type":"tags","id":"10899"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26146"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26150"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26184"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75615"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMany parasitic helminths can infect humans by penetrating directly through intact skin. This process requires specific adaptations that allow the parasites to breach the skin barrier.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how parasitic helminths actively penetrate human skin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["By passive diffusion through skin pores","Through pre-existing skin wounds only","By dissolving keratin proteins only","By inducing host cells to engulf them","By secreting proteolytic enzymes and mechanical force"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct mechanism is \u003Cstrong\u003Esecreting proteolytic enzymes and mechanical force\u003C/strong\u003E. Parasitic helminths like hookworms (\u003Cem\u003EAncylostoma duodenale\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003ENecator americanus\u003C/em\u003E), \u003Cem\u003ESchistosoma\u003C/em\u003E species, and \u003Cem\u003EStrongyloides stercoralis\u003C/em\u003E actively penetrate intact skin using a combination of enzymatic degradation and mechanical disruption of the epidermis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBy dissolving keratin proteins only\u003C/strong\u003E - While helminths do break down skin proteins, they require both enzymatic and mechanical methods\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBy passive diffusion through skin pores\u003C/strong\u003E - Helminths are too large for passive diffusion and require active mechanisms\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrough pre-existing skin wounds only\u003C/strong\u003E - While wounds may facilitate entry, these parasites can penetrate intact skin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBy inducing host cells to engulf them\u003C/strong\u003E - Helminths are too large to be phagocytosed by host cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe proteolytic enzymes break down proteins in the skin\u0027s extracellular matrix, while mechanical force from the parasite\u0027s muscular movements helps create a path through the tissue. This combination allows efficient penetration of the skin barrier.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hookworms use proteolytic enzymes and mechanical force to actively penetrate intact skin.","Schistosoma cercariae secrete enzymes that break down skin proteins to enable penetration.","Strongyloides larvae can directly penetrate skin using both enzymatic and mechanical methods."],"references":["Murray PR, Rosenthal KS, Pfaller MA. Medical Microbiology. 8th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61133"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18543"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61133"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T12:36:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T12:39:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11275"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75615"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.